</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">6</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">6</td></tr><tr><td style=\"text-align:center\">7</td><td style=\"text-align:center\">2</td></tr></table></div>\n\n(a) (i) (b) Find the mode.\n\n(c) Calculate the mean.\n\n(d) Omar wants to show the information from the table in a pie chart.\nCalculate the sector angle for the people who visited the cinema 5 times."},{"id":"0580-2018MayJune-Paper21-Q24","paper":"2018MayJune-Paper21","qnum":24,"marks":6,"topics":["Coordinate geometry","Geometry"],"s":"3.7","d":2,"cat":"coord","topic":"Perpendicular lines","qtype":"perpendicular lines","g":"mixed","src":"0580/21/M/J/18 Q24","year":2018,"session":"MayJune","tex":"(a) Point A has co-ordinates (1, 0) and point B has co-ordinates (2, 5).\nCalculate the angle between the line AB and the x-axis.\n\n(b) The line PQ has equation y = 3x - 8\n\nand point P has co-ordinates (6, 10).\n\nFind the equation of the line that passes through P and is perpendicular to PQ.\nGive your answer in the form y = mx + c.\n\ny =  [3]","parts":[{"label":"(a)","marks":3},{"label":"(b)","marks":0}],"hasFigure":false,"cognitive":"apply","cmd":"calculate"}]